03889nam a22005175i 9780300268935DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002689357 a10.12987/97803002689352doi  a(DE-B1597)638255  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aBP174 7aREL0370102bisacsh04a297223/eng/202209121 aPatel, Youshaa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Muslim Difference :bDefining the Line between Believers and Unbelievers from Early Islam to the Present /cYoushaa Patel. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b20 b-w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Style -- tIntroduction: “Whoever imitates a people becomes one of them,” -- t1 Turning Away from Christians and Jews? -- t2 From Narrative to Normative -- t3 Empire of Small Differences -- t4 The Symbolic Power of Muslim Difference -- t5 Ibn Taymiyya and the Innovation of Imitation -- t6 “A person belongs with the one he loves,” -- t7 Escaping the Devil’s Lair: Ghazzī between Spirit and Law -- t8 Can Muslims Wear European Hats? -- tEpilogue: Seeing the Other in the Light of God -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA sweeping history of Muslim identity from its origins in late antiquity to the present How did Muslims across time and place define the line between themselves and their neighbors? Youshaa Patel explores why the Prophet Muhammad first advised his followers to emulate Christians and Jews, but then allegedly reversed course, urging them to “be different!” He details how subsequent generations of Muslim scholars canonized the Prophet’s admonition into an influential doctrine against imitation that enjoined ordinary believers to embody and display their religious difference in public life. Tracing this Islamic discourse from its origins in Arabia to Mamluk and Ottoman Damascus, colonial Egypt, and beyond, this sweeping intellectual and social history offers a panoramic view of Muslim identity, revealing unexpected intersections between religion and other markers of difference across ethnicity, gender, and status. Patel illustrates that contemporary debates in the West over visible expressions of Islam, from headscarves and beards to minarets and mosques, are just the latest iterations in a long history of how small differences have defined Muslim interreligious encounters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aIslamxCustoms and practices. 0aIslamxRelations. 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073923740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300268935?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300268935423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300268935/original  a978-3-11-073923-7  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY